    "markdown": "## MRI Leg Overview\n\n### What is an MRI Leg?\nAn \\*\\*MRI Leg\\*\\* is a painless scan that uses powerful magnets and radio waves to create detailed pictures of bones, muscles, tendons, ligaments, and blood vessels in your leg.\n### How it differs from X-ray or CT\n- \\*\\*X-ray\\*\\* shows bones only and uses radiation.\n- \\*\\*CT scan\\*\\* uses radiation and is better for bone detail.\n- \\*\\*MRI Leg\\*\\* shows \\*\\*soft tissues\\*\\* clearly and has \\*\\*no radiation\\*\\*.\n\n## Risks & Limitations of the Leg MRI\n\n### Contrast allergy risks\n- Rare reaction to gadolinium contrast dye\n- Inform staff of any previous allergies\n### Claustrophobia considerations\n- Open-bore MRI machines available\n- Mild sedation offered if needed\n### Metal implant restrictions\n- Pacemakers, cochlear implants, or metal fragments may limit scan\n- Full screening done before appointment\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During the Leg MRI\n\n- \\*\\*Bone integrity\\*\\* – detects fractures, bone bruises\n- \\*\\*Ligament & tendon status\\*\\* – checks for tears or inflammation\n- \\*\\*Cartilage thickness\\*\\* – evaluates joint wear (osteoarthritis)\n- \\*\\*Soft-tissue masses\\*\\* – identifies cysts, tumors, or abscesses\n\n## Reasons for Taking a Leg MRI\n\n- \\*\\*Unexplained pain\\*\\* – when X-rays appear normal\n- \\*\\*Swelling evaluation\\*\\* – to rule out infection or clot\n- \\*\\*Post-injury assessment\\*\\* – to plan surgery or rehab\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Test\n\n- \\*\\*No radiation\\*\\* – safe for children and pregnant women (after first trimester)\n- \\*\\*High-resolution images\\*\\* – shows millimeter-level detail\n- \\*\\*Early detection of pathologies\\*\\* – catches problems before they worsen\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with Leg MRI\n\n- \\*\\*Stress fractures\\*\\* – tiny cracks from overuse\n- \\*\\*ACL/PCL tears\\*\\* – knee ligament injuries\n- \\*\\*Osteoarthritis\\*\\* – cartilage loss and bone spurs\n- \\*\\*Tumors or cysts\\*\\* – benign or malignant growths\n\n## Preparing for Leg MRI\n\n### Instructions\n- Wear loose, metal-free clothing\n- Remove jewelry, watches, and hairpins\n- Fast 4 hours only if contrast is planned\n### Prerequisites\n- Bring previous reports and doctor’s prescription\n- Fill out safety screening form\n### Best time to take the scan\n- Morning slots reduce waiting time\n- Avoid scheduling during acute pain flare-ups\n### Eligibility\n- Adults and children above 5 years\n- Pregnant women after first trimester (non-contrast)\n---\n## Procedure for Taking an MRI Leg\n### Step-by-step guide\n1. Change into hospital gown if needed.\n2. Lie on the scanner table; leg is positioned in a coil.\n3. Earplugs or headphones reduce machine noise.\n4. Stay still for 20–40 minutes.\n5. Contrast dye is injected halfway if required.\n### Duration and what to expect\n- \\*\\*20–40 minutes\\*\\* total\n- Loud knocking sounds are normal\n- No pain; slight warmth if contrast is used\n---\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n- \\*\\*Remove metal objects\\*\\* – keys, coins, belts\n- \\*\\*Inform about implants\\*\\* – pacemaker, screws, or plates\n- \\*\\*Pregnancy considerations\\*\\* – notify staff if pregnant or breastfeeding"
